# Orchesty Integration Worker

This project is an Orchesty integration worker. It connects external services via connectors, batches, and mappers that are orchestrated by the Orchesty platform. The worker can run as a standalone Node.js application with a dev server or inside Docker, and registers itself with an existing Orchesty instance.

All source code lives in `src/`. The SDK is `@orchesty/nodejs-sdk`. Pre-built connectors for various services are available as `@orchesty/connector-*` packages.

## Architecture

- **Application** — handles authentication (OAuth2 / Basic / Client Credentials) and builds authenticated HTTP requests.
- **Connector** — calls a single API endpoint; delegates auth to its Application.
- **Batch** — like a connector but processes paginated / bulk data. Called repeatedly by the platform (one page per invocation).
- **CustomNode** — pure data transformation (mapper / filter); no HTTP calls, no application dependency.

## Registration

Every element **must** be registered in `src/index.ts`.

Use `container.setNode()` for **all nodes** (Connector, Batch, CustomNode). This ensures the SDK injects `db` (MongoDbClient) and `sender` (CurlSender) automatically. Use `container.setApplication()` only for Applications.

**Never** use the low-level `container.setConnector()`, `container.setBatch()`, or `container.setCustomNode()` directly — they skip dependency injection and cause runtime errors like "MongoDbClient has not been set."

For **Connectors and Batches** that call an API, pass the Application instance as the **second argument** to `setNode()`. Without it, the node won't know which application to use for authentication and will throw "Application has not been set." CustomNodes (mappers / filters) don't need an application.

```typescript
// OAuth2 applications require the OAuth2Provider from the container
import { OAuth2Provider } from '@orchesty/nodejs-sdk/dist/lib/Authorization/Provider/OAuth2/OAuth2Provider';

const oauth2Provider = container.get(OAuth2Provider);

// OAuth2 Application — pass provider to constructor
const app = new MyOAuth2App(oauth2Provider);
container.setApplication(app);

// Basic/Client Credentials Application — no constructor args
const basicApp = new MyBasicApp();
container.setApplication(basicApp);

// Connector — pass application as 2nd arg
container.setNode(new MyConnector(), app);

// Batch — pass application as 2nd arg
container.setNode(new MyBatch(), app);

// CustomNode (mapper / filter) — no application needed
container.setNode(new MyMapper());
```

## Topology Payload Flow

Every node in a topology receives its input via `dto.getJsonData()` and must set its output via `dto.setJsonData()` (or `dto.setNewJsonData()` / `dto.setData()`). The output of one node becomes the input of the next.

When designing a topology, **plan the payload shape at each step**:

1. **Base connectors** define their own minimal input/output contract (e.g. `{ id: string }` in, raw API response out).
2. **Derived connectors** adapt between the topology payload and the base connector contract — they extract what the base needs from the upstream payload and merge the API result back for the downstream node.
3. **CustomNodes (mappers)** reshape data between different payload formats (e.g. ServiceA record -> ServiceB record).

Example payload flow for a sync topology:

| Step | Node | Input payload | Output payload |
|------|------|---------------|----------------|
| 1 | ListItems (batch) | `{}` | single item from ServiceA |
| 2 | LookupInServiceB | item | `{ ...item, serviceBId }` |
| 3 | Mapper | `{ ...item, serviceBId }` | `{ serviceBRecord }` |
| 4 | CreateInServiceB | `{ serviceBRecord }` | ServiceB response |

## Official Connector Packages

Pre-built connectors for many services are available on npm under the `@orchesty` scope. Search for them at: https://www.npmjs.com/search?q=%40orchesty%2Fconnector

Install only the packages your integration needs, e.g. `npm install @orchesty/connector-hubspot`. Each package typically provides an Application class and ready-made connectors that you import and register in `src/index.ts` alongside your custom nodes.

